Exercise 4

Read and analyze the following blog post. Select two of the worst visualizations (in your opinion) and comment why are they worst. Then select two of the best/most interesting visualizations (in your opinion) and comment on what is good about them.

Solution:

Good data visualization should provide an effective graphic representation of the data. It should enable the audience to understand the important message(s) from the data and it should communicate information clearly and efficiently to users. Good data graphics must avoid distorting what the data have to say. In addition, they must emphasize the important concepts, relations and numbers. The representation must provide context and it must be coherent. Also, clear and detailed labelling should be used.

In the provided example we can see one data set represented in 25 different ways. The graphs represent life expectancy data by country, from 2000 to 2015. The best two data representations are:

The data is sorted and clearly represented and we can easily compare how life expectancy varies from one country to another. In the second graph an additional information about the life expectancy of man and woman is added. This is done in simple and coherent way and the main message is not distorted.

The worst two data representations are:

Here the main information (life expectancy in different countries) is not clearly represented and the labeling is not clear. Moreover, due to the overlapping lines it is impossible to compare and understand the life expectancy. Clearly, this method of representing data compared to the bar graphs used before is not appropriate.

Exercise 5

We will need to repeat some probability theory. Read the first chapter on Probability theory from MathWiki web-site: http://mathwiki.cs.ut.ee/start. We recommend that you solve all the given exercises for training purposes. Play with the simulation of a dice. Explain how the increase of rolling times changes the probability distribution of the dice.

Solution:

Rolling a fair dice results in 6 elementary events, which have equal probability \(\frac{1}{6}\).
Obviously the minimum number of rolls of a fair dice to see all sides is \(6\). The expected time required to roll every number is \(14.7\) and the probability for this is \(0.015\). So we expect to roll a dice about \(15\) times on average before we observe all sides at least once. Using a table we can represent the elementary events with probabilities. This is called a probability distribution of an experiment/process (in our case probability distribution of the dice roll). The idea is that, each time you perform the experiment, you obtain a sample of the random variable. Since the variable is random, you expect to get different values as you obtain multiple samples. Using a large enough sample implies that even if a certain number has an increased probability, in a long run the other underrepresented numbers will appear enough times for the probability of every number to converge to \(\frac{1}{6}\) as the sample size increases.

Solve the following tasks from Math wiki, describe it in detail (not just an answer) and make sure you can explain them for the audience:

A company makes computer discs. It tested a random sample of discs from a large batch and found that the probability of any disc being defective is \(0.025\). Bob buys two discs. Calculate the probability that

  1. both discs are defective;
  2. that only one disc is defective.
  3. The company found \(4\) defective discs in the sample they tested. How many discs were likely tested?

Solution:

  1. The probability that none of the discs works equals the probability that both discs fail. This is given by:

\[P(both fail)=P(F)P(F)=0.025*0.025=0.000625\] b. If only one disc works then you could select the two discs in the following orders: \((FW)\) or \((WF)\). Hence:

\[P(W)=1-0.025=0.975\] \[P(one fail)=P(W)P(F)+P(F)P(W)=0.04875\] c. The number of the sample is \(160\) disks. There are two approaches to solve this problem. First we can create a simple ration which will give us the number of nondefective disks.

\[\frac{4}{x}= \frac{0.025}{0.975}\]

\[x=156\] If we add the 4 defective disks we get \(160\).

Also we can use the formula of the classical probability which will give us the same result.

\[0.025=\frac{4}{x}\]

Also this type of problem is easily solvable using the binomial distribution.
